The synthesized nanoparticles are characterized using UV–Vis spectra (

                        Fig. S1a

                     ) where the cPDA/TiO2 have shown a distinct π-π* transition at 258 nm whereas f-cPDA/TiO2 and CD have shown the π-π* transition at 231 and 234 nm with n-π* transition at 307 and 313 nm respectively. The formation of the f-cPDA/TiO2 polymer dot was confirmed by the excitation-dependent change in the emission behavior (

                        Fig. S1b

                     ). Further FTIR spectra (

                        Fig. S1c

                     ) was conducted to check the surface functionality of the nanoparticles. The shifting of the characteristic peak of Ti–O–O stretching vibrations of TiO2 from 682 cm−1–656 cm−1 and the N–H vibration of cPDA shifts from 1506 to 1496 cm−1 explains successful conjugation of cPDA and TiO2 in cPDA/TiO2. The appearance of Si–O peak of f-cPDA/TiO2 at 1103 cm−1 was shifted to 1087 cm−1 for CD exhibited successful loading of cPDA/TiO2 with cPDA/TiO2 to form CD. To control the solubility of the particles in the CD-hydrogel, nanoparticle size is an important parameter, the evaluation of hydrodynamic diameters upon visible light treatment is shown in Fig. 1b. The size of the nanoparticle decreases from 586 nm to 468 nm after visible light treatment due to the photocatalytic effect of the particles. The light tunable solubility was further accessed by comparing the dispersibility of the particles in the solution (

                        Fig. S2a

                     ). The CD particles without light treatment precipitated very fast (

                        Figs. S2a–d

                     ), due to the large size and hydrophobicity while the CD particles after light treatment are comparatively stable due to the smaller size and hydrophilicity. The CD possesses excellent tunable fluorescence properties (

                        Fig. 1

                     c) [17]. Without any visible light treatment, the fluorescence intensity of the CD almost quenches due to the Förster resonance energy transfer (FRET) mechanism, where the f-cPDA/TiO2 and cPDA/TiO2 particles are present in an aggregated state [18]. After exposure to visible light, the photocatalytic effect induces the hydrophobic–hydrophilic transformation that increases the distance between the particles, thereby preventing the FRET phenomenon. As a result, the fluorescence intensity increases, and fluorescence maxima is observed at 495 nm against an excitation wavelength of 360 nm [18]. The confocal microscopic fluorescence image of the particles (

                        Fig. S3

                     ) also evidenced the regaining of fluorescence property of the nanoparticle solution after visible light treatment. In the X-ray diffraction (XRD) pattern (Fig. 1d), the CD show a wide diffraction peak at a 2θ value of 22.15° before visible light treatment, owing to the presence of sp2-hybridized graphitic carbon, which becomes narrower and exposes the crystalline planes of TiO2 after visible light treatment for 9 h, implying that the particles containing sp2-hybridized graphitic carbon become more dispersed and expose the planes of TiO2 after treatment [19]. This phenomenon was further confirmed by transmission electron microscopy (TEM) analysis of the CD. As shown in Fig. 1e, the morphology of the CD exhibited the quasi-spherical shape and confirms the decrease in particle size after 9 h visible light treatment. The appearance of crystalline characteristics after visible light treatment can be observed in the selected area electron diffraction (SAED) pattern. As detected in the HR-TEM image of the inset, the CD contains a lattice fringe whose spacing is 0.23 nm and close to the graphite (100) crystal plane, while the presence of cross planes indicates that the CD shows a high degree of crystallinity after visible light treatment [20]. The lattice spacing also decreases from 0.23 nm to 0.21 nm for lattice contraction [21]. X‐ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) analysis was presented in Fig. S4. Fig. S4a shows the XPS survey spectrum, which confirms the presence of O, Ti, N, C and Si. The O1s XPS data (Fig. S4b) show a small peak of about 534.1 eV is related to OC/C–O⋯Ti. The presence of C–O⋯Ti originates from the bond between TiO2 and PDA [22]. Fig. S4c exhibits the narrow Ti 2p XPS spectrum where the Ti2p1/2 shoulder at a binding energy of 460.2 eV corresponds to the Ti3+ generated after visible light treatment [22]. Fig. S4d shows the C1s XPS data; the π‐π* transition corresponds to the satellite peak centered at 290.7 eV. CC of the benzene ring. The corresponding binding energy peaks at 285.6, 286.4, and 288.3 eV are attributed to the C–N, C–O, and CO bonds, respectively [23]. Moreover, the XPS data is consistent with the electrocatalytic behavior of the PDA/TiO2 nanoparticles [22]. Confocal imaging was used to determine the distribution of nanoparticles as well as the fluorescence in the CD-hydrogel-coated PET surface. In Fig. S5, blue emission is observed after 9 h exposure to visible light, whereas the CD-hydrogel without exposure does not show any fluorescence due to FRET. After visible light irradiation, the aggregation of the nanoparticles is eliminated with an increase in the distance between the nanoparticles due to increased solubility, resulting in the inhibition of the FRET phenomenon and enhancement of fluorescence of the CD-hydrogel coated PET surface. To further analyze the roughness of the CD-hydrogel surface, the atomic force microscopy (AFM) analysis was carried out with the CD-hydrogel-coated silicon wafer (Fig. 1f). The height profile of the surface (

                        Fig. S6

                     ) is deeper before visible light treatment, which becomes smoother after visible light exposure, further confirming the small size and uniform distribution of CD within the hydrogel after visible light treatment. Photoelectrochemical techniques are frequently used to qualitatively study photogenerated charge carrier excitation and transfer in photocatalysts. Therefore, transient photocurrent responses of the CD-hydrogel were measured during multiple on-off cycles with irradiation of visible light. (Fig. S7). The photocurrent response of the CD-hydrogel film increases with an increase in the exposure time, revealing electron-hole pairs՚ excellent separation efficiency under visible light irradiation [24]. This result is likewise in line with the intensity of the PL, suggesting the enhanced photocatalytic activity of the CD-hydrogel film after visible light treatment.

The contact angle measurements show that the contact angle is 87.3° before visible light treatment, while it decreases to 57.6° after visible light exposure for 9 h, indicating the hydrophobic-to-hydrophilic transformation (Fig. S8a,b). The change in the wettability affects the water permeability and swelling ratio which influence the mechanical strength and electrical properties. As shown in Fig. S8c, for the CD-hydrogel before visible light exposure, the swelling ratio reaches a maximum of 86% due to the presence of hydrophobic perfluorosilica in the CD-hydrogel system. After visible light irradiation, the hydrophilic transformation results CD-hydrogel affording a maximum swelling ratio of 225% [25]. The FTIR spectra of the hydrogel (

                        Fig. S9

                     ) before and after visible light treatment have shown the shift of O–H vibration frequency from 3410 to 3385 cm−1 indicating that a strong hydrogen bonding interaction was arising due to the release of cPDA resulting in enhanced hydrogen bonding interaction due to hydrophilic change. The conductive properties of the CD-hydrogel were investigated under the AC signal (Fig. 2
                     a). The conductivity increases with an increase in the visible light treatment time and is almost saturated after 9 h visible light treatment. Compared to the CD-hydrogel under dark conditions, the electronic conductivity is nearly four-fold (1.3 vs. 5.2 mS m−1). With a decrease in the particle size, the cPDA is released as a result the hydrogen bond-promoted delocalization of charge carriers is generated when exposed to visible light. Additionally, the hydrophilic transformation facilitates the migration of charged species that is responsible for an increase in conductivity [26]. The change in the resistance value observed from the source meter with respect to the visible light treatment time follows a descending order, further confirming the decrease in the charge transfer resistance upon visible light treatment (

                        Fig. S10

                     ). The small sizes of the particles and uniform distribution of the CD after visible light irradiation in the hydrogel matrix are also confirmed based on the TEM data (

                        Fig. S11

                     ). The CD-hydrogel without visible light treatment is soft and brittle but becomes stronger and more stretchable after visible light treatment, indicating its enhanced strength after visible light irradiation (Fig. 2b). It has been noticed that if the irradiation time further increased from 9 h there is no significant improvement in the conductivity and stretchability of the hydrogel, according to the observation 9 h irradiation time was fixed for all instances. Moreover, the visible-light-treated CD-hydrogel can be stretched freely and manually extended up to 321% of its original length without cracking (Fig. 2c). Additional analysis of the stress-strain characteristics of the CD-hydrogels reveals that by varying the visible light treatment time the mechanical strength and flexibility can be tuned (Fig. 2b). With a maximum tensile strength of 0.27 MPa at an elongation at break of 212% possessing Young's modulus of 24.23 kPa, the untreated CD-hydrogel exhibits a typical tensile stress-strain curve for weak polymeric hydrogel. In contrast, the CD-hydrogel subjected to visible light treatment has higher stress in comparison to the untreated hydrogel. With a treatment time of 9 h, the stress of 0.83 MPa, elongation at break of 531% with Young's modulus of 84.87 kPa was achieved, revealing that visible light treatment improved the CD-hydrogel's stretchability and mechanical strength simultaneously. The self-recovery ability of CD-hydrogels was assessed using cycle loading-unloading experiments at 100% strain, the results are presented in Fig. S12(a) and (b). The hysteresis loop and stress of CD-hydrogels show a clear drop when compared to the first cycle which means that during the loading-unloading process the strain, could not be fully restored. In the case of visible light treated hydrogel, the low hysteresis area with negligible strength degradation and plastic deformation demonstrates excellent fatigue resistance. Under compression, it is obvious that after the visible light treatment, the modulus and compressive strength drastically increased from 236 KPa to 827 KPa (Fig. S12c). Simultaneously, the fracture strain also increased from 78.17% to 102.66%. Significantly, the loading and unloading curves at 60% compression (

                        Fig. S12d

                     ) indicated that the visible light hydrogel had an excellent shape-retaining ability. The rheological performance of the prepared CD-hydrogels was further evaluated. The linear viscoelastic region (LVE) was first established by measuring the strain sweep where strain independent behavior of storage modulus (G′) and loss modulus (G″) were observed [27]. LVE displays the strain tolerance gradually increases with an increase in the visible light treatment time and is the highest for the CD-hydrogel after 9 h treatment (

                        Fig. 2

                     d). The crossover point (where G″ = G′) value-enhanced from 31% to 78% for the CD-hydrogel after 9 h visible light treatment. The dynamic rheological test results in Fig. S13 have shown that the visible-light-induced transformation increases the value of G′ significantly from 0.52 kPa to 5.83 kPa by strengthening the CD network within the CD-hydrogel. Fig. 2e and f shows the strain alternation experiment for the effective viscoelastic recovery of the CD-hydrogels, indicating their stability and reversibility capabilities. Fig. 2e shows that upon the application of >35% strain for, the gel becomes viscous (G″ > G′) for the CD-hydrogel without any visible light treatment. Notably, for the visible-light-treated CD-hydrogel (Fig. 2f), after the application of 75% strain, the gel rapidly returns to its initial form, indicating the reversible characteristics of the material [28]. Differential scanning calorimetry (DSC) analysis was performed before and after visible light irradiation (Fig. 2g), which showed that the glass transition temperature increased from 102 °C to 108 °C, whereas the melting temperature increased from 216 °C to 220 °C [29]. The results clearly indicate the hydrophobic-to-hydrophilic transition increases the hydrogen bonding interaction, which increases the mechanical strength and stretchability.
